I. INTRODUCTION AND SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT

     This case presents one of the most egregious patterns of parental interference, false allegations, and systematic deprivation ever to come before this Court. Over the past 22 months, Defendant/Mother Emily A. Watson has deprived Plaintiff/Father Andrew J. Pigors of 329+ days of contact with his five-year-old son through a calculated campaign of:

     • False allegations to police (poisoning, assault, threat, mental instability)
     • False allegations to medical providers (suicidality, danger to child)
     • False allegations to courts (emergency danger requiring ex parte suspension of parenting time)
     • Procurement of a fraudulent Personal Protection Order
     • Systematic gatekeeping and parental alienation
     • Willful violation of court-ordered parenting time
     • Abuse of ex parte emergency procedures (5 suspension orders spanning 6 months)

     Every single allegation Defendant has made has been conclusively disproven by:
     • Medical records (no poisoning, no injuries, no mental health diagnosis)
     • Police investigation reports (no criminal basis, no charges filed)
     • HealthWest psychological evaluation (no safety concerns, no mental health issues, Father appropriate caregiver, alienation by Mother documented)
     • Court records (this Court awarded equal legal custody on July 17, 2024, which would be unconscionable if Defendant's threat allegations were true)

     Despite this overwhelming exculpatory evidence, Defendant has succeeded in depriving Father of 329+ days of contact with his child, including:
     • 39 days (March 28 - May 5, 2024): Unilateral withholding
     • 26 days (October 20 - November 15, 2024): Withholding
     • 192+ days (August 8, 2025 - Present): Ongoing ex parte suspension
     • 72 additional days: Various other periods

     This 329+ days of deprivation represents nearly 11 months—effectively erasing Father from the child's life.

     The child has been deprived of his father.
     The father has been deprived of his son.
     Both have suffered irreparable harm.

     This must stop. Now.

SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT

     Father seeks modification of the July 17, 2024 custody order to establish joint physical custody with equal parenting time (182.5 overnights each per year), or alternatively, to designate Father as the primary physical custodian.

     This modification is warranted because:

     1. PROPER CAUSE EXISTS: Defendant has systematically violated parenting time (329+ days), engaged in documented parental alienation, made false allegations proven by professional evaluation and investigative records, and obtained a fraudulent PPO to manipulate custody.

     2. CHANGE OF CIRCUMSTANCES EXISTS: Since the July 17, 2024 order, the parent-child relationship has been completely eliminated through 192+ continuous days of deprivation, professional documentation of alienation has been obtained, false allegations have escalated, and Defendant has demonstrated absolute unwillingness to facilitate the relationship.

     3. BEST INTERESTS FAVOR MODIFICATION: Applying the twelve statutory factors under MCL 722.23, nine factors favor Father, one favors Mother, and two are equal. The most critical factor—willingness to facilitate the relationship (factor j)—overwhelmingly favors Father, as Mother has engaged in systematic gatekeeping and deprivation totaling 329+ days.

     4. EQUAL PARENTING TIME SERVES THE CHILD: Joint physical custody with equal parenting time restores the arrangement that existed before court involvement, maximizes the child's time with both parents, prevents future gatekeeping, and complies with MCL 722.27a's strong presumption favoring parenting time.

     5. MAKEUP TIME REQUIRED: Father is entitled to 329 days of makeup parenting time to repair the damaged parent-child relationship.

     6. ATTORNEY FEES WARRANTED: Mother's bad faith conduct has necessitated this motion and justifies an award of attorney fees.

     The evidence is overwhelming. The legal basis is clear. The child's best interests demand modification. Father respectfully requests that this Court grant the relief requested.

