II. STATEMENT OF FACTS

A. Background and Procedural History

     1. The Parties and the Child

     Andrew J. Pigors (Father) and Emily A. Watson (Mother) are the parents of L.D.W., born in 2019. Ex. 1 (Birth Certificate). The child is now five years old. The parties were never married but maintained a relationship and shared parenting arrangement for several years following the child's birth.

     2. Pre-Litigation Parenting Arrangement (2019-2024)

     From the child's birth until court involvement in 2024, Father and Mother maintained an informal shared parenting arrangement. Father exercised approximately 182.5 overnights per year (50% parenting time). Ex. 2 (Parenting Time Ledger 2019-2024).

     During this period:
     • Father provided daily care, including feeding, bathing, clothing, transportation
     • Father attended the child's medical appointments
     • Father maintained a stable home environment appropriate for the child
     • Father provided financial support
     • The child developed a strong bond with Father
     • No allegations of abuse, neglect, or safety concerns were raised
     • No involvement with Child Protective Services
     • No police investigations or criminal charges

     Id. See also Ex. 3 (Father's Affidavit ¶¶ 5-18).

     3. Mother's First False Allegations (October 2023 - June 2024)

     In October 2023, Mother began making false allegations against Father, claiming Father was suicidal and mentally unstable. Ex. 4 (Police Report 10/15/23); Ex. 5 (Medical Records 10/15/23).

     Police responded and conducted a welfare check. Father was found to be stable, appropriate, and presented no danger. No mental health hold was initiated. No hospitalization occurred. Id.

     In June 2024, Mother made a second suicidal allegations. Again, police and medical evaluation found no basis. Ex. 6 (Police Report 6/8/24); Ex. 7 (Medical Records 6/8/24).

     Medical records from both incidents show:
     • No suicidal ideation
     • No mental health diagnosis
     • No prescribed psychiatric medication
     • No recommendation for treatment
     • No danger to self or others

     Ex. 5, Ex. 7.

     4. Father Files for Custody; Mother Files Fraudulent PPO (June-November 2023)

     Recognizing the need for formal custody orders, Father filed for custody in June 2024. Ex. 8 (Custody Complaint).

     In response, Mother filed for a Personal Protection Order (Case No. 2023-5907-PP) on November 17, 2023, alleging that Father had threatened her and posed a danger. Ex. 9 (PPO Petition).

     The PPO was granted ex parte on November 17, 2023. Ex. 10 (Ex Parte PPO).

     Mother's allegations in the PPO included:
     • Father threatened her
     • Father is dangerous
     • Father poses a risk to the child
     • Father is mentally unstable

     Ex. 9.

     All of these allegations are false and have been disproven by subsequent evidence, as detailed below.

     5. Custody Trial and July 17, 2024 Order

     A custody trial was held in July 2024. Father proceeded pro se. Mother was represented by counsel.

     The trial was marked by significant procedural irregularities:
     • Father's ability to present evidence was restricted
     • Father's witnesses were limited
     • Hearsay evidence favorable to Mother was admitted over objection
     • Father's objections to Mother's evidence were overruled
     • The trial was conducted in a manner that favored Mother

     Ex. 11 (Trial Transcript).

     On July 17, 2024, the Court entered an Order Regarding Custody and Parenting Time. Ex. 12 (7/17/24 Order). That order:

     • Granted joint legal custody to both parents
     • Granted primary physical custody to Mother
     • Granted Father 79 overnights per year

     Id.

     This represented a 56.7% reduction in Father's parenting time, from 182.5 overnights per year to 79 overnights per year—a loss of 103.5 overnights annually. Ex. 13 (Parenting Time Calculation).

     Significantly, the Court awarded equal legal custody to both parents, implicitly finding that both parents were fit and appropriate to make major decisions regarding the child. This finding is completely inconsistent with Mother's allegations of threat, danger, and mental instability. Ex. 12.

