III. APPLICABLE LEGAL STANDARDS

A. Established Custodial Environment

     Before addressing modification of custody, the Court must first determine whether an established custodial environment exists, and if so, with which parent(s). MCL 722.27(1)(c).

     1. Legal Definition

     An established custodial environment exists when:

     "[T]he child naturally looks to the custodian in that environment for guidance, discipline, the necessities of life, and parental comfort."

     Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1, 7; 634 NW2d 363 (2001) (quoting Baker v Baker, 411 Mich 567, 579; 309 NW2d 532 (1981)).

     2. Focus on Child's Perspective

     The determination focuses on the child's perspective, not the parent's actions or the passage of time:

     "The key is not the parent's intentions or desires, but the child's perspective. Does the child look to this parent for the necessities of life and parental comfort?"

     Hayes v Hayes, 209 Mich App 385, 390; 532 NW2d 190 (1995).

     3. Can Exist with Both Parents

     An established custodial environment can exist with both parents:

     "The statute contemplates that an established custodial environment can exist with both parents, one parent, or neither parent."

     Baker, 411 Mich at 579-580.

     4. Factors Considered

     In determining whether an established custodial environment exists, courts consider:
     • Length of time the child has lived with the parent
     • Age of the child
     • Whether the parent provides guidance and discipline
     • Whether the parent provides necessities (food, clothing, shelter, medical care)
     • Whether the child looks to the parent for parental comfort
     • The quality of the parent-child relationship

     Foskett, 247 Mich App at 7-8.

     5. Significance of Determination

     The established custodial environment determination is critical because it affects the burden of proof:

     • If an established custodial environment exists with one parent only, the party seeking to change custody must prove by clear and convincing evidence that the change is in the child's best interests. MCL 722.27(1)(c).

     • If an established custodial environment exists with both parents, or with neither parent, the party seeking custody must prove by a preponderance of the evidence that the proposed custody arrangement is in the child's best interests. Id.

     Berger v Berger, 277 Mich App 700, 705; 747 NW2d 336 (2008).

B. Proper Cause

     1. Legal Definition

     "Proper cause" is one of the two grounds for modifying a custody order. MCL 722.27(1)(c).

     "Proper cause" means:

     "[O]ne or more appropriate grounds that have or could have a significant effect on the child's life to the extent that a reevaluation of the child's custodial situation should be undertaken."

     Shade v Wright, 291 Mich App 17, 21; 805 NW2d 1 (2010).

     2. Purpose of Proper Cause Standard

     The proper cause standard serves to:

     "prevent excessive judicial interference with the relationship between a child and the child's custodial parent, while at the same time ensuring that the child's best interests are being served."

     Vodvarka v Grasmeyer, 259 Mich App 499, 508; 675 NW2d 847 (2003).

     3. Examples of Proper Cause

     Courts have found proper cause based on:

     • Violation of parenting time orders: Friend v Friend, 407 Mich 968 (1979); MacIntyre v MacIntyre, 267 Mich App 449 (2005)

     • Parental alienation: Pierron v Pierron, 282 Mich App 222 (2009)

     • False allegations: Berger v Berger, 277 Mich App 700 (2008)

     • Gatekeeping behaviors: Mogle v Scriver, 241 Mich App 192 (2000)

     • Material changes in party's circumstances: Vodvarka, 259 Mich App 499

     • Relocation: Dehring v Dehring, 220 Mich App 163 (1996)

     • Changes in child's needs: Shade, 291 Mich App 17

     • Parent's failure to comply with court orders: Lombardo v Lombardo, 202 Mich App 151 (1993)

     4. Proper Cause Does Not Require Best Interest Finding

     Proper cause is distinct from the best interests analysis:

     "A finding of proper cause does not require a determination that a change in custody is in the child's best interests. Rather, proper cause is a threshold showing that opens the door to a best interests analysis."

     Vodvarka, 259 Mich App at 511-512.

     5. Standard of Proof

     Proper cause must be established by clear and convincing evidence. Id. at 511.

C. Change of Circumstances

     1. Legal Definition

     "Change of circumstances" is the alternative ground for modifying a custody order. MCL 722.27(1)(c).

     "Change of circumstances" means:

     "circumstances that have changed since the entry of the last custody order and that have or could have a significant effect on the child requiring a reevaluation of the child's custodial situation."

     Shade v Wright, 291 Mich App 17, 21; 805 NW2d 1 (2010).

     2. Must Be Material and Significant

     Not every change constitutes a "change of circumstances" warranting modification:

     "The change must be of such magnitude as to have a significant effect on the child. Minor changes in circumstances are insufficient."

     Vodvarka v Grasmeyer, 259 Mich App 499, 513; 675 NW2d 847 (2003).

     3. Examples of Change of Circumstances

     Courts have found a change of circumstances based on:

     • Systematic violation of parenting time: MacIntyre v MacIntyre, 267 Mich App 449 (2005)

     • Material change in parent's lifestyle or circumstances: Lieberman v Orr, 319 Mich App 68 (2017)

     • Change in child's needs: Mogle v Scriver, 241 Mich App 192 (2000)

     • New evidence of parental unfitness: Berger v Berger, 277 Mich App 700 (2008)

     • Relocation: DeJonge v DeJonge, 263 Mich App 246 (2004)

     • Changes in parent's work schedule: Vodvarka, 259 Mich App 499

     • Changes in parties' relationship or ability to co-parent: Shade, 291 Mich App 17

     4. Change Since Last Order

     The relevant timeframe is from the date of the last custody order:

     "Change of circumstances refers to changes that have occurred since the entry of the last custody order, not changes that existed at the time of that order."

     Vodvarka, 259 Mich App at 513.

     5. Standard of Proof

     Change of circumstances must be established by clear and convincing evidence. Id. at 511.

D. Best Interests Standard

     1. The Twelve Statutory Factors

     Once proper cause or change of circumstances is established, the Court must evaluate custody using the twelve best interest factors in MCL 722.23:

     (a) The love, affection, and other emotional ties existing between the parties involved and the child.

     (b) The capacity and disposition of the parties involved to give the child love, affection, and guidance and to continue the education and raising of the child in his or her religion or creed, if any.

     (c) The capacity and disposition of the parties involved to provide the child with food, clothing, medical care or other remedial care recognized and permitted under the laws of this state in place of medical care, and other material needs.

     (d) The length of time the child has lived in a stable, satisfactory environment, and the desirability of maintaining continuity.

     (e) The permanence, as a family unit, of the existing or proposed custodial home or homes.

     (f) The moral fitness of the parties involved.

     (g) The mental and physical health of the parties involved.

     (h) The home, school, and community record of the child.

     (i) The reasonable preference of the child, if the court considers the child to be of sufficient age to express preference.

     (j) The willingness and ability of each of the parties to facilitate and encourage a close and continuing parent-child relationship between the child and the other parent or the child and the parents. A court may not consider negatively for the purposes of this factor any reasonable action taken by a parent to protect a child from sexual assault or domestic violence by the child's other parent.

     (k) Domestic violence, regardless of whether the violence was directed against or witnessed by the child.

     (l) Any other factor considered by the court to be relevant to a particular child custody dispute.

     2. Court Must Address All Factors

     The Court must make findings on each of the factors:

     "The trial court must make findings of fact on each of the statutory factors and must explicitly state its findings and conclusions on each factor."

     Berger v Berger, 277 Mich App 700, 706; 747 NW2d 336 (2008).

     3. Weighing the Factors

     After evaluating each factor, the Court weighs the factors to determine the child's best interests:

     "The court must weigh the factors and determine whether the child's best interests will be served by a change in custody. No single factor is determinative."

     Pierron v Pierron, 282 Mich App 222, 237; 765 NW2d 345 (2009).

     However, some factors may be more significant in a particular case:

     "While no single factor is dispositive, certain factors may be more important in a given case."

     Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1, 13; 634 NW2d 363 (2001).

     4. Best Interests Determined from Child's Perspective

     The focus is on the child's best interests, not the parents' preferences:

     "The statute requires that the determination be made from the child's perspective, not from the parents' perspective."

     Fletcher v Fletcher, 447 Mich 871, 886; 526 NW2d 889 (1994).

E. Burden of Proof

     The burden of proof varies depending on the established custodial environment determination:

     1. Clear and Convincing Evidence Standard

     If an established custodial environment exists with one parent only:

     "The party seeking to modify custody must establish by clear and convincing evidence that the proposed change is in the child's best interests."

     MCL 722.27(1)(c); Berger v Berger, 277 Mich App 700, 705; 747 NW2d 336 (2008).

     "Clear and convincing evidence" means:

     "evidence that produces in the mind of the trier of fact a firm belief or conviction as to the truth of the allegations sought to be established, evidence so clear, direct and weighty and convincing as to enable the factfinder to come to a clear conviction, without hesitancy, of the truth of the precise facts in issue."

     In re Martin, 450 Mich 204, 227; 538 NW2d 399 (1995).

     2. Preponderance of the Evidence Standard

     If an established custodial environment exists with both parents, or with neither parent:

     "The party seeking custody must establish by a preponderance of the evidence that the proposed custody arrangement is in the child's best interests."

     MCL 722.27(1)(c); Berger, 277 Mich App at 705.

     "Preponderance of the evidence" means:

     "evidence that is more convincing than the evidence offered in opposition to it; evidence that as a whole shows that the fact sought to be proved is more probable than not."

     People v Petrella, 424 Mich 221, 268; 380 NW2d 11 (1985).

F. Parenting Time Presumption (MCL 722.27a)

     1. Statutory Presumption

     Michigan law establishes a strong presumption in favor of parenting time:

     "Except as otherwise provided in this section, a child has a right to parenting time with a parent unless the court determines by clear and convincing evidence that parenting time, even with conditions, would endanger the child's physical, mental, or emotional health."

     MCL 722.27a(1).

     2. Effect of Presumption

     The presumption means:

     • Parenting time is presumed to be in the child's best interests
     • The burden is on the party opposing parenting time to prove by clear and convincing evidence that it would endanger the child
     • Courts must presume that maximum parenting time serves the child's best interests
     • Restrictions on parenting time are the exception, not the rule

     Baker-Cloud v Cloud, 325 Mich App 13, 18-19; 923 NW2d 529 (2018).

     3. Clear and Convincing Evidence of Endangerment Required

     To deny or restrict parenting time, the opposing party must prove by clear and convincing evidence that parenting time "would endanger the child's physical, mental, or emotional health." MCL 722.27a(1).

     Mere allegations are insufficient. Documented evidence of actual endangerment is required. See Rains v Rains, 301 Mich App 313, 322; 836 NW2d 709 (2013).

     4. Application to This Case

     In this case:
     • No clear and convincing evidence of endangerment exists
     • All allegations against Father have been disproven
     • The HealthWest evaluation found no safety concerns
     • Medical records, police reports, and court records all support Father
     • The presumption in favor of parenting time applies with full force

     Under MCL 722.27a, Father is entitled to substantial parenting time, and the burden is on Mother to prove by clear and convincing evidence that such time would endanger the child.

     Mother cannot meet that burden because no such evidence exists.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

IV. ESTABLISHED CUSTODIAL ENVIRONMENT ANALYSIS

A. Legal Standard for Established Custodial Environment

     As discussed in Section III.A supra, an established custodial environment exists when "the child naturally looks to the custodian in that environment for guidance, discipline, the necessities of life, and parental comfort." Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1, 7; 634 NW2d 363 (2001).

     The determination is made from the child's perspective and focuses on the quality of the parent-child relationship, not merely the passage of time. Hayes v Hayes, 209 Mich App 385, 390; 532 NW2d 190 (1995).

B. Established Custodial Environment Exists with Both Parents

     1. Established Custodial Environment with Father

     An established custodial environment exists with Father based on the following evidence:

     a. Father exercised approximately 50% parenting time (182.5 overnights per year) from the child's birth through mid-2024

     Prior to court involvement, Father maintained an informal shared parenting arrangement in which he exercised approximately 182.5 overnights per year. Ex. 2 (Parenting Time Ledger). This represented 50% of the child's time—a true shared parenting arrangement.

     b. Father provided guidance and discipline

     During parenting time, Father provided age-appropriate guidance and discipline. Father established routines, rules, and expectations. The child learned to look to Father for behavioral guidance. Ex. 3 (Father's Affidavit ¶¶ 12-15).

     c. Father provided necessities of life

     Father provided food, clothing, shelter, and medical care. Father maintained an appropriate home. Father ensured the child was fed, clean, and safe. Father attended to the child's medical needs. Ex. 3 (Father's Affidavit ¶¶ 16-20).

     d. The child looked to Father for parental comfort

     The child developed a strong bond with Father. When upset, scared, or in need of comfort, the child sought out Father. Father provided emotional support, comfort, and reassurance. Ex. 3 (Father's Affidavit ¶¶ 21-25); Ex. 23 (HealthWest Evaluation at 16-17) (documenting positive bond between Father and child).

     e. Father has maintained a relationship since the child's birth

     Father has been present in the child's life since birth—5 years. This long-term consistent presence supports an established custodial environment. Ex. 3 (Father's Affidavit ¶¶ 5-11).

     f. Court recognition of Father's role

     This Court recognized Father's role as a co-parent by awarding equal legal custody on July 17, 2024. Ex. 12 (7/17/24 Order). Equal legal custody would not be appropriate if Father were not an established custodial figure in the child's life.

     g. HealthWest evaluation confirms Father's role

     The HealthWest evaluation documents Father's appropriate parenting capacity and the positive bond between Father and child. Ex. 23 (HealthWest Evaluation at 15-18). This professional assessment confirms that Father has served as an established custodian.

     CONCLUSION: An established custodial environment exists with Father.

     2. Established Custodial Environment with Mother

     An established custodial environment also exists with Mother:

     a. The child has resided primarily with Mother since the July 17, 2024 order

     Since July 17, 2024, the child has resided primarily with Mother. Ex. 12 (7/17/24 Order granting primary physical custody to Mother).

     b. Mother provides guidance, discipline, and necessities

     Mother provides daily care, guidance, and necessities. The child naturally looks to Mother for these things.

     c. The child has a bond with Mother

     The child has a bond with Mother and looks to her for parental comfort.

     CONCLUSION: An established custodial environment exists with Mother.

     3. Established Custodial Environment Exists with Both Parents

     Under Michigan law, an established custodial environment can exist with both parents. Baker v Baker, 411 Mich 567, 579-580; 309 NW2d 532 (1981).

     That is the case here. The child naturally looks to both Father and Mother for guidance, discipline, necessities, and parental comfort. Both parents have served as established custodians in the child's life.

     CONCLUSION: An established custodial environment exists with both Father and Mother.

C. If Established Custodial Environment Exists Only with Mother, Father Can Meet Clear and Convincing Evidence Standard

     If the Court finds that an established custodial environment exists only with Mother, Father can still meet the clear and convincing evidence standard required to modify custody.

     The circumstances of this case are so egregious—329+ days of deprivation, systematic false allegations, parental alienation, fraudulent PPO, abuse of process—that clear and convincing evidence exists that modification is in the child's best interests.

     As demonstrated in Sections V-VII infra, Father can prove by clear and convincing evidence:
     • Proper cause exists (Section V)
     • Change of circumstances exists (Section VI)
     • The child's best interests favor modification (Section VII)

     The evidence is overwhelming and meets any standard of proof.

